    - ["mp3331019",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.pool.AsyncResult.__dict__,        "__ixor__"], false]
    - ["mp3331020",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.pool.MapResult.__dict__,          "__ixor__"], false]
    - ["mp3331021",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers.SyncManager.__dict__,    "__ixor__"], false]
    - ["mp3331022",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers.BaseListProxy.__dict__,  "__ixor__"], false]
    - ["mp3331023",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers._BaseDictProxy.__dict__, "__ixor__"], false]
    - ["mp3331024",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers._BaseSetProxy.__dict__,  "__ixor__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __iand__, __ior__, __ixor__ across all 8 mp subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 8 classes x 3 methods = 24 rows.
# __iand__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __ior__:  false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __ixor__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# All 24 values are false.
# The _BaseSetProxy finding is the most analytically significant result in
#   this wave. set itself defines all three in-place set-algebra operators:
#   __iand__ (in-place intersection, s &= t), __ior__ (in-place union,
#   s |= t), and __ixor__ (in-place symmetric difference, s ^= t).
#   Yet _BaseSetProxy.__dict__ contains none of them. The proxy wraps a
#   managed set object living in a separate server process; in-place operators
#   would need to rebind the caller's local variable to the return value,
#   which is semantically incompatible with transparent proxy forwarding.
#   No in-place proxy forwarding is implemented in _BaseSetProxy.
# managers._BaseDictProxy note: dict defines __ior__ (Python 3.9+) for
#   in-place merging. _BaseDictProxy does not expose __ior__ in its __dict__
#   for the same proxy-incompatibility reason.
# Wave 661 already established that the forward operators __and__, __or__,
#   and __xor__ are all false for all 8 mp types (including the proxies).
#   The in-place variants tested here are absent for both the same reasons
#   (non-proxy types have no set/dict algebra) and the additional proxy
#   reason (_BaseSetProxy does not forward in-place operations).
# multiprocessing is a process-based concurrency library; its types interact
#   exclusively through explicit method calls, subprocess lifecycle management,
#   and IPC — never through Python's in-place augmented assignment operators.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

